< Review>
Arrived at about 9:25 in the evening with a TON of laundry. Didn't feel rushed at all. The cleaning lady there as well as the other customers were all very nice and friendly. The facility was very clean. The equipment was all relatively new and in good order and worked well. The free Wi-Fi was definitely a nice touch, and the prices for the washers and dryers was actually a little bit less than many other laundromats I've been to, where the equipment isn't even as good.</Review>

< Text>
I loved the customer service provided by Jenny when I got my unit. However, aside from that, I was disappointed, I went back the next day and asked to borrow a dolly and was told they didn't have any left because they let 1 family borrow all of them and they did not make an attempt to offer to retrieve one. As a paying customer I expect to be entitled to one especially when all of them are being used by one family who had a smaller unit and I'm sure I paid more than them. In addition, only 1 day after having the unit. Although the gate is open till 9pm the door that leads to the inner unit was closed. This is unacceptable especially when I only have 2 more days to move. I called the 800# only to waste my time and called the regional manager Kristie or Kristine only to reach her vm with no call back. Very disappointed and should have driven further to avoid this mess of a storage place. PS you will have to buy a cylinder lock that will run you $20+ dollars unlike at other public storages where you can use a regular lock.<//Text>

We had just watched Bohemian Rhapsody at the Grand Lake theater and wanted something yummy for dinner. I saw the sign for Chao and remember it being good years ago. <review>Pretty good and fairly accurate with Thai flavors you'll get in Thailand. Prices are comparable to what you pay at Bay Area Thai places, portion sizes are fair to generous depending on what you order.  Staff is friendly, nice spot and worth a try - you may end up a regular customer :)
Definitely recommended dishes are their curries, stired fried eggplant & green beans (prik king) dishes.  However, if you like your pad Thai on the dry side and noodles more firm, don't order (pad Thai here is decent flavor wise but is a little too mushy/soggy, noodles too soft).<//review><Pics>[{'url': ['https://lh5.googleusercontent.com/p/AF1QipMhJsDRqAX6yKcanNtY7rJg7xUKxuYb9cOMhPSC=w150-h150-k-no-p']}, {'url': ['https://lh5.googleusercontent.com/p/AF1QipNA1zyRwctlFxtsZP6boFMHwdFa0YL0WK1WsdGy=w150-h150-k-no-p']}]< /Pics><response>None< /response><GmapID>0x808f8743e4394aa3:0x3dea7ec89438532f< /GmapID></record></dataset><record>

Shoutout from the ATL. This Thai restaurant is better than most in Atlanta. Everything was flavorful and on point. Ordered 5 dishes: combo appetizer, crab fried rice, pad Thai, mango salad, seafood stir fry, tom yum gong, and two others to go. All dish were on point. If lacking that punch, be sure to ask for the spice tray. Super friendly service and dishes served in a timely manner. Again, better than most in Atlanta!</Text>

<text>I asked the salesperson at the hardware store on Ocean Ave what was the best Chinese restaurant in the area; since we were new in town.  He pointed down the street and said Golden China......so my son and I gave it a try.

We walked in and were greeted by the friendly owner.  I mentioned that her place was referred to us; and she proceeded to tell us that they had been in business over 30 yrs...same location.   She was extremely warm and gracious.

I ordered a combination plate and my son had General chicken and we split a sweet and sour soup.  We received large portions of everything and the food was very, very tasty.

Ironically we had tried almost every Chinese restaurant in the area but somehow missed this one until today.

My son said what I was already thinking.....this will be our 'go to' Chinese restaurant from now on.< /text><Gmap_id>0x808f7dcd97eda0e9:0xf30064da54e6d75d< /Gmap_id></record></dataset><record>

<text>As far as Japanese grocery stores go, we in the Los Angeles area are pretty fortunate. We have Nijiya, Mitsuwa, and others though few are as big as this branch of Tokyo Central. You can find not only the standard fare of snacks, groceries, and Japanese food staples but there are also restaurants as well as a whole floor of home goods, tshirts and so on. Definitely worth a stop if you are in the area.</text><UserId.>117141325247266466888</UserId.><gmapID>0x80c2b56685ac2169:0xae5fe05abe26b2<//gmapID>< Resp>

The grocery had a lot of Japanese items to choose from, it was really hard to pick & choose which ones to buy. It had a second floor that looks like a department store that sells dry goods like kitchen ware, clothes, appliance and Japanese trinkets. They do have Anime figurines, clothing & accessories too. There were a good variety of restaurants in the food court and the food was great.< /text>

<user_id>116841891464563933682<//user_id>< review>
Best Japanese food and kitchen supermarket Ive been to outside of Japan.  They even have a Hawaiian products aisle.
Good produce selection, terrific sushi and seafood, and wonderful, noodles, sauces, and spices from Japan.  Best yet, many of the labels on the shelves explain and differentiate the productsvery helpful when selecting a Shoyu sauce, soba noodle, or seaweed package.
Also, dont forget to check upstairs for clothing, slippers, toys, suitcases, and other products.<//review>

The best Japanese supermarket in Los Angeles. It's well stocked. I found everything I needed. Sea asparagus, fresh octopus, fish meatballs, etc. They have a big parking lot. It's crazy that they are associated with Don Quixote, a cheap department type store, which I went to in Tokyo.</Review>

I LOVE this store. They try their best to label everything in English to make it more accessible to folks.

If youre going to buy the plates make sure you show up before 7. At 7 pm they go on sale for 20% off but by then there's little to nothing left. People come in a little before 7 and stack their carts. Come earlier and pay full price if you really want to be able to have options.< /Review>

< review>
Very clean inside.  Due to Covid-19 protocol, limited people were allowed inside the market.  But the line moves very fast.  They have some good fresh vegetables, fruits and meat section.  They have this Passion Orange Guava (POG) in 1 quart carton at the refrigerator section.  They also have one of the best deal in bento boxes meal.  A box costs between 5.99 to 6.99.  Fresh sushi, maki rolls, all at a good price.</review>

<Rating>5< /Rating><review>The best Japanese supermarket. Not only is Tokyo Central designed culturally appreciate, but also you can find various Japanese food, snacks, and cultural heritage merchandise.

Tokyo Central Market is huge, clean, and well organized. Unfortunately, due to the COVID-19 pandemic era, the upper stores are closed.

When you are inclined to have Japanese food, enjoy a quick look at what Japanese culture looks like, come visit Tokyo Central Market.

You wont be disappointed.<//review><Pics>[{'url': ['https://lh5.googleusercontent.com/p/AF1QipOPhWGa84fSV8cyPSRvLSTvFWLAvb7KffE_NcE=w150-h150-k-no-p']}, {'url': ['https://lh5.googleusercontent.com/p/AF1QipO8D4YEeYcy0MEh-N29GYCrz35Emg14U4-FVd4=w150-h150-k-no-p']}, {'url': ['https://lh5.googleusercontent.com/p/AF1QipNjYYzaFfYD3HE58FOMpMRLjynhGG-U6_cXAOM=w150-h150-k-no-p']}, {'url': ['https://lh5.googleusercontent.com/p/AF1QipP8dTjejcMi18UUSCOBBRjr1VdmVw1u2mZ020M=w150-h150-k-no-p']}, {'url': ['https://lh5.googleusercontent.com/p/AF1QipM2ft6zIWFzCk0eGaKpIro3q64MDa3FB2wBjHw=w150-h150-k-no-p']}, {'url': ['https://lh5.googleusercontent.com/p/AF1QipOkBV5POv6G_fiLzW-ZfIt39JK_zuZg4m9ic4o=w150-h150-k-no-p']}, {'url': ['https://lh5.googleusercontent.com/p/AF1QipOByV88Eqap8m1g6PbGfjbFUECAqnEO5nQ6Df4=w150-h150-k-no-p']}, {'url': ['https://lh5.googleusercontent.com/p/AF1QipPPmKuWA3Nb9a42qORplIX_wLfxLEIDWXIOQ6Y=w150-h150-k-no-p']}, {'url': ['https://lh5.googleusercontent.com/p/AF1QipMRNZt6fHKrLHOwYsCfv42sqjXVaQyCIX2v67o=w150-h150-k-no-p']}, {'url': ['https://lh5.googleusercontent.com/p/AF1QipPMEKlidCaqTffckLvjdrfyufwbYWNeKl89xnE=w150-h150-k-no-p']}, {'url': ['https://lh5.googleusercontent.com/p/AF1QipN2Fwh1uTCupaCh0nKZx2BHYZ7mtclVYT4W8yA=w150-h150-k-no-p']}, {'url': ['https://lh5.googleusercontent.com/p/AF1QipMuM-Q8dQivYlZU2IAH3YpaNcjFPwSxnremBV8=w150-h150-k-no-p']}, {'url': ['https://lh5.googleusercontent.com/p/AF1QipNIlLHkqS55uI0uL02F4wbjpUxMDK6ivusXnnY=w150-h150-k-no-p']}, {'url': ['https://lh5.googleusercontent.com/p/AF1QipOr9aDMDaZBo_I6doDFrHAJO27FE88U57JZC20=w150-h150-k-no-p']}, {'url': ['https://lh5.googleusercontent.com/p/AF1QipPzYSV3JaG7PXC-Ohmv7C6DUdopEhZqo7sK1NE=w150-h150-k-no-p']}]<//Pics><Response>None</Response>< gmap_id>

<UserId.>115308441379422799570< /UserId.><Review>The best prices in town for Japanese and Hawaii food items. It looks like the Don Quixote group is taking over, but I don't think that will impact the great prices. They also bring in unique food items and Japan regional fares. Right now it's strawberry season so they have cool but super expensive Japanese strawberries. The food court is also outstanding - the karaage chicken at Tenkatori is pretty awesome.
The down sides are minor stuff. I realize that they need to pack in product but I wish it was easier to maneuver the aisles. Many barely fit two carts going in opposing directions. Also the parking spaces tend to be on the tight side, and they don't have adequate very return stations.</Review></record>

< Review>
I had so much fun here! My husband and I got katsu from the food court, which was amazing. I haven't had katsu this good since I was in Japan. Then I had some fun browsing the retail items upstairs, ended up buying a few gifts for my friends who like kawaii things. The household items look pretty solid too, memory foam pillows, top of the line rice cookers, etc. I was kind of surprised they didn't have a bigger variety of Asian veggies (like 99 ranch, H-Mart). But they do have those Japanese strawberries (a real delicacy).</Review>

< review>
I love this place, but I wish they took covid more seriously at this location. For some reason management doesn't seem to care about the health of there customers at this specific location. Baskets aren't wiped down, the number of people in the store isn't monitored and there are plenty of customers allowed to walk around maskless.

We try not to go to this location, if possible, because other Tokyo Centrals in L. A. Do a great job so we drive 30 minutes longer to be safer.

They would normally get 5 stars but Management's disregard of safety is just too big a deal for me and my family.</review>

< text>
My wife, who is Japanese, and I started to go to TCM Redondo Beach Blvd and Artesia Blvd at the beginning of the pandemic. Now we rarely go to the Ralph's in our neighborhood. The meat selection at TCM is 1000 times better than Ralph's for cooking Japanese food because it is sliced properly. Moreover, the fruits and vegetables are the freshest and cheapest. The Mammoth Bakery inside the TCM on RB Blvd is our favorite place to buy sliced bread, perfect for breakfast toast. We can get Crystal Geyser Water for only 79 cents a gallon! We can also get very Japanese vegetable, fruit, and herb we need there. The Artesia Blvd one has great restaurants and a bakery inside. They also have the best selection of meat and bento, IMO. I loved their karaage chicken deli, but they closed it. Their 2nd floor has character goods, cooking appliances, and clothes. My wife occasionally gets stuff up there. I love their various "fairs." We got a lot of stuff during their KAGOSHIMA Fair. It is so cool to be able to get the real taste of Japan here in So Cal.<//text>

<user>109853269621737522930<//user><user_name>David Chien<//user_name>< date>
1605836603075</date>
< rate>
5< /rate>
< Text>
The BEST in LA!
Seriously Huge and Packed with just about Everything you could want from a Japanese supermarket and goods store. Makeup, detergent, furniture, stationary, gifts, home goods, electronic dictionaries, air conditioners, cookware, kitchen goods, stuffed animals, phone accessories, car scents, etc etc etc. Just Huge and the biggest, most well-stocked shop period among all of the Tokyo Central, Nijiya, Mitsuwa, and other Japanese supermarket centers in Los Angeles.
A handful of restaurants from takoyaki to karage for takeout.
Latest corona remodel gets rid of the antique furniture $$$, closed the dining (can still take out), adds a big stationary section with more pens and pencils than Kinokuniya, even more housewares, beauty supplies, tons of boxed take out meals, etc.
And prices are among the lowest at Japanese markets in L.A.
Seriously, the ONLY Japanese supermarket you need to shop at - a mini Bic Camera or Yodabashi!!</Text>

<Date>1612966737704< /Date><Rate>4</Rate>< Review>
$2.87 for a bag of ORGANiC ginger; as of february 2019.

This market caters to customers that have high standards for quality produce. The mandarin fruits are consistently of high quality. Its not the cheapest market to shop for produce but there are always deals for some of the items. You can save yourself some serious dollars if you keep checking what is on sale and when.

Ping me for any additional questions. I am happy to help.

< Text>
This used to be marukai but I guess they got bought out by Tokyo central. It's still pretty much the same though except the dining area got upgraded especially the outdoor part. This market has a big Japanese cosmetics, lifestyle, home goods area which I love! I think if I ranked the Japanese market this would be on top closely after nijiya. Mitsuwa is prettier but it doesn't have as many items. Also this market has the best chicken karaage in their food court. Always super crowded ( which is bad during this pandemic) but theres a reason why so many people go here.</Text>

<UserId.>106146170388544342263<//UserId.><username>Cynthia Ashton</username><Date>1478359002884< /Date>< rating>
5< /rating>
< Text>
Love this japanese market, it has everything you need if you are in need of Japanese food and food. Has basic everyday household Japanese appliances, rice cooker, humidifier, hot water maker, dishes, cups, and a bunch of other cute useful Japanese things you want but you don't need. Awesome food selection, lots of reasonably priced fresh vegetables and fruit. Has organics and imports from Japan. Fresh fish from Japan and local, at reasonable prices. The meat selection is amazing the best meat you could probably get anywhere. The snacks and all Japanese ingredients you need they will have it at a good price.

They also have a food court area if you come during the busy hours of the day. The pork buns are amazing. Sometimes it gets busy so pick wisely what time if the day you decided to go. The structure is difficult to get in on Artesia. I use to pass it a few times before i was able to identify it. It's surrounded by a green fence all around.<//Text>

< review>
I just love Marukai (forever will i call it that!) Love exploring and finding new things. Fresh veggies, fruits, love their snacks, love the whole grocery part. Also prepared food selection is great. Meat dept is small but has good quality meat. The food court is slowly coming back. The Tokyo croissant place is awesome! If you love the Japanese culture, then come to this place. <Name>Wesley Krueger</Name><gmap_id>0x80c2b56685ac2169:0xae5fe05abe26b2< /gmap_id>< Response>
None</Response>
<userid>109214225129615227111</userid>< review>
This place was originally known as Marukai, I'm not sure when they changed the name. Inside you can find a couple small restaurants, groceries, and novelty products.

Downstairs, they have a large selection of meats, vegetables and drinks/beer. Also available are many Japanese snacks and candy (these alone make a trip worth it in my opinion).

Upstairs, their products range from furniture to figurines. They have a lot of novelty and comfort items, including the full size pajamas with a hood known as kigurumi, and blind boxes containing random cute figurines.

This store can make for a fun browsing experience, and can also satisfy a grocery trip. I can only caution that with all of the neat things they have here is that you might spend more money than you plan to.</review>

J S< /username>
<review>I love this Japanese market. It is HUGE. The sushi section is awesome. It rivals any restaurant sushi for 2/3 of the price. Fresh and yummy. Besides all the great Japanese and Hawaiian grocery items they have a whole area with plates, rice cookers, and kitchenware as well as a gift and pop toy section upstairs. They also have a wellness area.

I also like the fresh mochi and desserts they each week from Fugetsu Do and the hot food restaurants inside. From karage to Gindaco, a ramen place, a tonkatsu place, and a Japanese pastry shop. They also have a croquette and onigiri deli in the corner as well as karage.

If you want bug cuts of fish for sushi, simply go to the butchery in the back of the store.

The Tokyo Central in Torrance is much smaller and driving to the one in Gardena is worth it.< /review></record>

< Text>
I recommend this place especially for anyone that cooks, and is looking for Japanese ingredients.  The perishables here are generally more fresh than what you're likely to find at similar Japanese markets in the area.  You can also find prepared food, kitchen goods, cosmetics, and various knickknacks all in one convenient location.
Note though that the discounted prices throughout the market require a membership card at the cost of $1 (with no recurring fees).<//Text>

<userid>116733847310475342493<//userid><name>J & A< /name><Date>1562889645800<//Date><rating>5<//rating>< text>
This place has everything you can think of for a Japanese market. It's really a mega store. Deli, fresh sushi counter, a few fast food stands, inside & outside eating areas, grocery store with impressive selections of Japanese goods, very fresh produce, well stocked liquor area (could not find Okinawan saki unfortunately). The downstairs also houses a separate cosmetics section, it is so big it is a little overwhelming & I honestly didn't know what half the stuff was meant for since I'm not able to read the letters. It also has a separate appliances area with rice cookers and small things like that. The upstairs has all the fun stuff. Things like kimonos (some moderate priced used ones) wooden sandals, cute hair clips, Zen gardens, lucky cats, dolls, trinkets, stuffed animals, crazy socks, kigurumi (onesies), costumes, models, Pokemon stuff.
Also, everyone that works here is super helpful if you have questions about anything so don't hesitate to ask.
Overall, you could spend a few hours exploring this place, shopping, having lunch & have a great time doing it.< /text>

My badge in clear sight.

As I approached the register,
i noted there was a guest services.

Without hesitation she quickly replied no.

I noted the registers all around were giving change.

I repeated are you sure?

She did not give a reason.
For example,

I had to " Purchase" something,
or it's their policy not to give Change!

I am on duty,
well groomed, dressed in uniform.

The wrong nationality in my opinion.

Her body language left me feeling..

Like a Foreigner in his Homeland!

It's kind of ironic, as I was born
in Japan & am of Indian and English descent!
Therefore I am a Native to this land...

This place has everything you can think of for a Japanese market. It's really a mega store. Deli, fresh sushi counter, a few fast food stands, inside & outside eating areas, grocery store with impressive selections of Japanese goods, very fresh produce, well stocked liquor area (could not find Okinawan saki unfortunately). The downstairs also houses a separate cosmetics section, it is so big it is a little overwhelming & I honestly didn't know what half the stuff was meant for since I'm not able to read the letters. It also has a separate appliances area with rice cookers and small things like that. The upstairs has all the fun stuff. Things like kimonos (some moderate priced used ones) wooden sandals, cute hair clips, Zen gardens, lucky cats, dolls, trinkets, stuffed animals, crazy socks, kigurumi (onesies), costumes, models, Pokemon stuff.
Also, everyone that works here is super helpful if you have questions about anything so don't hesitate to ask.
Overall, you could spend a few hours exploring this place, shopping, having lunch & have a great time doing it.<//Review>

<Text>Very clean and friendly. They had everything I needed</Text><user_name>Loriann Garoutte< /user_name><Rating>5< /Rating></record>

< rating>
5</rating>
<name>John Jiao</name><userid>115366180693589039249</userid><gmapID>0x80c2b56685ac2169:0xae5fe05abe26b2</gmapID>< text>
I'm a Hawaii native, so I've been exposed to a lot of American-Japanese food/culture/etc, and this place is easily the BEST Japanese market I've ever been to. If you're into Hawaiian food, there's multiple aisles of stuff I've literally never seen outside of Hawaii before --- authentic portugeuse sausage, lau lau, every single type of sugary drink (POG, passion orange, etc), even frozen Zippys meals (!!!)

From a Japanese standpoint, everything is not only directly imported, but there are little English descriptions of all the foods on the price labels. All the staff are super courteous, and the food court attached is out of this world!

A real shining star here is the sushi --- it's cheaper, fresher, and tastier than you'll be able to get anywhere else that I've ever seen. There's also an authentic Japanese curry stand in the back corner where you can get all kinds of amazing curry dishes. The food court has some of the best karaage chicken I've ever had, and this is the first time I've seen an authentic takoyaki stand in LA.

All in all, amazing service, amazing prices, and a must-go for anybody who loves Japanese food.< /text>

None</resp>

<Text>Tokyo Central, my favorite Japanese grocery store is the mother of all Japanese supermarkets having not only the first floor w/ mostly comestibles & dry goods, but also having a second floor that specializes in furniture & Japanese objets d'art.

Nijiya is a good place to run in fast to get a few items, but for  the sheer variety of goods such as reasonable cosmetics, Sak猫 (sah keh), Japanese beers, Sho-chu-/Japanese lower alcohol Vodkas, snacks, produce, Japanese food in cans, frozen, plastic, produce Tokyo Central can't be beat.

There is something for everybody, at least for those interested in Japanese products.  If you're in here for the first time prepare to stay for about an hour to see what is available & acquant yourself to the layout. The proof is in the pudding; you have to go there.</Text><name>Gary I.</name></record>

<Date>1409949486922<//Date><Rate>4</Rate>< Review>
Boo to memberships. That being said, you can still enter and purchase items without a membership. They will charge an extra dollar and you dont get the sale prices, but at least you can still shop. They have one day memberships available if needed. The top floor is filled with Japanese items such as traditional clothing, furniture and unique d茅cor items and the main floor is filled to the brim with Japanese and Hawaiian groceries. On weekends there are sample food carts dishing out simple Japanese dishes to try. The food court is small but sufficient. Avoid at all costs around New Years.<//Review>

107915918624618371469< /userid>
<name>Mo Mo< /name>< Date>
1532326046954<//Date>
< Rate>
5<//Rate>
< Review>
This place has it all as far as a Japanese style market goes.

It has all the dry goods to make whats popular at home. All the frozen goods to take home and eat and also a nice little fiod court area to get some pretty decent food.

The Store also has a floral area and a toys/Japanese hobby section even have the paints you need to paint them. Pretty cool!

There lots of cool japanese nicknacks and little gifts if you want to gift some one something cool.

The makeup area is massive. I think this is the second biggest part of the store. Ir has everything iou would need as far as makup is concerned. Cheap too. I mean its not a Sephora but you get the picture.

There is a ready food are that is nice to pick up a quick sushi roll or even a nagiri or rice roll. Im surprised i never have been here sooner. I always just go to Marukai, But this place I beleive is a branch off of Marukai in Torrance. So a hit!

If your looking for something Japanese. This is the place. For sure!< /Review>

< review>
They have POG. I love Hawaii and I love Hawaiian Mai Tais and the best ones are made with the truly Hawaiian drink of POG. I scoured the internet trying to find a place in SoCal (Los Angeles area) I could get POG and someone recommendes Marukai, and sure enough, they have it! Besides the original POG brand, they even have another brand that is basically the same thing just in case. So excited to find POG in the LA area. Besides that this is a true Japanese market with all authentic imported Japanese (and some Hawaiian) foods.<//review>

< username>
Brian Garant< /username>
< Resp>
None< /Resp>
<gmap_id>0x80c2b56685ac2169:0xae5fe05abe26b2<//gmap_id>< text>
One of, if not THE, best Japanese supermarkets in the Los Angeles area. My family has been going here for years and, more often than not, we always find what we need. The prices can skew a little high on some items, I find that I can usually do my produce shopping elsewhere and save a little, but in general the prices are fine. It can get a little cramped inside on weekends and you should absolutely be prepared for a wait in the checkout line. For years I shopped at their satellite store in West Covina (closed now, sadly) and while it was much closer that was about the only thing it had up on the Gardena store. Consistently clean and, aside from one experience with a belligerent employee, the staff is great. I've tried most of their competitors over the years and have consistently come back to Marukai.< /text>

<Review>This is one of the better Marukais. They have everything that you could want.  The service sucks, though.  It serves the Nisei (2nd gen) crowd vs Mitsuwa or Nijiya which serves more of the Issei (1st gen) or Japanese transplant crowd.
Marukai is generally the cheapest of the 3 Japanese market chains, but I feel that the quality also suffers a bit.  Korean markets are cheapest for pretty much everything, so if you have a good Korean market nearby, I would generally opt to go there over Marukai.< /Review><rate>4</rate><name>Lisa Umeda</name>< response>

<Text>I heart Murakai so much. I am much closer to the Little Tokyo location, but what I love about the Gardena Murakai is that it is way bigger and never gets as crowded as the Little Tokyo one. (We all want to avoid that moment when you and an elderly lady are eyeing that last packet of whatever...and you briefly wonder if it's socially acceptable to elbow her out of the way.)

I usually pick up saimin ingredients, my favorite snacks, and other packaged items so I can't speak for any of the hot food or even packaged pastries there...but they always have what I need and then some. Sure, I need a mini stapler and a panda-shaped mug. Sure, I need taro pancake mix and strawberry Kit Kats. Why the eff not? The cashiers are super nice as well.

I did knock off a star because I happened to use the bathroom once and it was...not pretty. Also, the place in general is grungy (probably just old) but well-organized and the aisles are always clean.< /Text>< user_name>

渚伴瑁℃芥惧扮抽<//Review>

</record></dataset><record>
< review>
(Translated by Google) Very well stocked Japanese supermarket. They sell prepared food ready to go. You will find all kinds of ingredients to prepare traditional Japanese food. The food prepared while later it is, they lower the price as they do in the supermarkets in Japan. If you want to try traditional Japanese fast food this is the best place. I visited it with my nephews and we brought many snacks and instant soups to try at home, my nephews were delighted and we returned the next day to buy more. Due to the covid they offer masks to be able to enter in case they forgot. I found some merchandising products from Studio Ghibli. The supermarket is worth a visit. The next time I travel to Los Angeles I will visit them again.
